SIMPLE: make-believe
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: make-believe
<hw>make"-be*lieve`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A feigning to
believe, as in the play of children; a mere pretense; a fiction; an
invention.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Childlike <xex>make-believe</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Tylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To forswear self-delusion and <qex>make-believe</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>M. Arnold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Make-believe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Make-believe
<hw>Make"-be*lieve`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Feigned;
insincere.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Make-believe</xex> reverence.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>G. Eliot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Imaginary; <as>as, the child had a
<ex>make-believe</ex> friend to whom he often talked</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maked</ent>⟦br⟧
